@course

id: topic:psychology-of-design-qmvr
title: The Psychology of Design
author: Jane Mitchell
description: How cognitive biases shape the way people interact with designed objects.
color: #6366f1
genres: design, psychology
relevant_for: ux-designers, product-managers

@segment
Foundations
FD

@package
Why Familiar Feels Right
Free

@text
For as long as humans have existed, decisions have started with the eyes.
Our ancestors judged safety by the shape of a shadow.
They chose food by color.
They trusted faces in less time than it takes to blink.
The brain still works this way.

@text
A psychologist ran a simple experiment, some decades before the internet existed.
He showed people a series of random shapes.
Some shapes appeared once. Others appeared dozens of times.
When asked which shapes they preferred, people chose the ones they had seen most often.
They did not remember seeing them.
They just preferred them.

@text
The experiment was repeated with faces, words, and sounds.
The result was always the same.
The more often something appeared, the more people said they preferred it.
It did not matter whether the exposure was conscious.
The preference formed anyway.

@text
This pattern shows up everywhere in designed objects.
A button layout that feels "right" often feels right because you have seen it before.
A brand you trust may be a brand you have simply encountered many times.
The feeling of comfort is not a judgment. It is a memory.
The next package looks at what color does to that same fast, automatic system.

@question
Why do people tend to prefer familiar shapes over new ones?

answer: The brain treats familiarity as a signal of safety.
consequence: That is the intuitive answer, and it fits the evidence. If something appeared before without causing harm, the brain registers it as safe.

answer: People are simply lazy and avoid new experiences.
consequence: The reason is not effort. The brain runs a fast, unconscious calculation about safety. It is not making a deliberate choice.

answer: Familiar shapes are objectively better designed.
consequence: The preference exists even for random shapes with no design behind them. Familiarity alone is enough.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The brain uses past exposure as a shorthand for safety. If something has appeared before without harm, it feels trustworthy, even without conscious memory of the exposure.
hint: Think about what "familiar" might signal to a brain built for survival.

@text
This pattern is called the <c:g>mere exposure effect</c:g>.
The more familiar something feels, the more we tend to prefer it.
It is not a conscious choice. It happens below awareness.
It affects everything from the music we enjoy to the brands we trust.
Designers use it without always knowing its name.

@true_false
People tend to prefer objects they have never seen before over objects they encounter regularly.

true: Novelty always wins, the brain prefers new things.
consequence: Research consistently shows the opposite. Repeated exposure builds preference, not boredom.

false: Familiarity builds preference, repeated exposure increases liking.
consequence: Right. This is the mere exposure effect. It shapes taste in music, brands, and interfaces.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Encountering something repeatedly makes us prefer it more. This holds even when we do not notice the repetition.
hint: How many times have you seen the logo of a brand you trust.

@reflect
A brand you trust more than its competitors, and whether that trust started with quality or with repetition: a phone brand, a coffee chain.
A button layout that feels "right" in an app, and whether you could explain why without mentioning habit: a save icon, a swipe direction.
A song you disliked at first but now enjoy, and how many times you heard it before the change: a radio hit, a friend's recommendation.

@package
What Color Does Before You Read a Word

@text
Before written language existed, humans already had a working color system.
They judged the ripeness of fruit by its shade.
They sensed danger from the red of blood or fire.
They felt calm under a blue sky.
Color has been carrying meaning for much longer than words have.

@text
Researchers have found that people form first impressions of a product within seconds.
Most of that impression is based on color.
Not on shape, text, or price.
Color reaches the brain before any of those.
A red button and a green button do not feel the same.
Even if they do the same thing.

@text
This is not just about preference. It is about speed.
The brain processes color before it processes text.
A warning sign works because it is red, not because of what it says.
A calming interface works because it is blue, not because of its layout.
Color is the first layer of communication in anything designed.
The next package asks what happens when there is too much to look at.

@question
Why does color have such a strong effect on first impressions?

answer: The brain processes color before it processes text or shape.
consequence: That is the core reason. Color arrives first. Everything else is read after the brain has already formed an impression.

answer: People learn color associations from advertising.
consequence: Advertising uses color associations, but those associations are older than advertising. Red meant danger long before it meant "sale."

answer: Color preferences are random and personal.
consequence: Some preferences are personal, but the speed of color processing is not. The brain reaches for color first regardless of taste.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Color is processed faster than text or form. The first impression of any product or screen is shaped by color before the content is read.
hint: Think about what you notice first when you open an app for the first time.

@text
This speed is why <c:g>color</c:g> is treated as a design decision, not a decoration.
A designer choosing a color is choosing the first message the brain will receive.
Red means urgency. Blue means calm. Green means permission.
These are not rules designers invented. They are patterns the brain already carries.

@true_false
Color preferences in design are mostly about personal taste and have no universal patterns.

true: True, color is subjective.
consequence: Some associations do vary by culture. But the speed at which the brain processes color is universal, and certain associations appear across many cultures.

false: False, many color associations are shared across cultures and rooted in biology.
consequence: Right. Red for danger, blue for calm, and green for safety appear across cultures. These are not taught. They come from how the brain processes the world.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Culture shapes some color meanings. But the basic associations, and the speed of processing, are rooted in biology.
hint: Do red and green mean the same on a traffic light everywhere.

@reflect
A color that makes you feel calm in an app, and whether you would feel the same if it were bright red: a banking app, a meditation app.
A warning you understood before reading the text, because the color told you first: a red notification badge, a yellow road sign.
A product whose color you associate with trust, and whether the trust would hold in a different color: a blue social network, a green messaging app.

@package
When the Screen Asks Too Much

@text
A cognitive psychologist published a paper, decades before the first smartphone, with a famous title.
The paper was about how much the brain can hold at once.
The answer was small: about 4 separate items.
Not 20. Not 10. About 4.
Every screen you use is competing for those 4 slots.

@text
Imagine opening an app with 12 buttons on the first screen.
Each button is a separate task your brain has to register.
After 4, the rest start to blur.
You are not reading them anymore. You are scanning.
If scanning does not help, you leave.

@text
Now imagine the same app, but the first screen has 3 buttons.
The rest are tucked behind a menu.
You read all 3 without effort.
You pick the one you need.
The app feels simple, and the reason is not the design. It is the number.

@text
This is why the best-designed interfaces feel obvious.
They are not smarter than complex ones. They just show less at once.
When a design asks the brain to hold more than it can, people stop trying.
This is the problem designers call <c:g>cognitive load</c:g>.

@question
Based on what you just read, which of these reduces cognitive load?

answer: Breaking complex tasks into smaller steps.
consequence: Exactly. Showing only what is needed, when it is needed, keeps the brain under its limit.

answer: Showing all options at once.
consequence: More options means more items competing for those 4 slots. That is exactly what creates the overload.

answer: Using icons without labels.
consequence: Icons without labels force the brain to guess meanings. That adds load, it does not reduce it.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Reducing cognitive load means reducing what the brain has to process at any moment. Showing less, not more, is almost always the answer.
hint: Think about what makes an interface feel easy versus overwhelming.

@true_false
Showing more information on a screen helps the user make better decisions.

true: True, more information means better choices.
consequence: Beyond a certain point, more information makes decisions worse, not better. The brain can only hold about 4 items at once.

false: False, too much information overwhelms the brain and slows decisions.
consequence: Right. The best interfaces reduce what is visible to what is needed right now. Everything else is hidden behind a clear path.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Cognitive load theory shows that the brain has a strict limit on how much it can process at once. Reducing visible options almost always improves the experience.
hint: Compare how a menu with 3 items feels versus one with 30.

@reflect
A screen that felt easy to use, and whether the ease came from good design or from fewer options: a checkout page, a settings menu.
A moment when too many choices made you stop choosing at all: a streaming service, a restaurant menu, an online store.
A form you abandoned halfway through, and whether the problem was the questions or the number of them: a signup, a survey.

@segment
Perception and Decisions
PD

@package
The First Number Wins

@text
When you are asked to estimate something you do not know, your brain looks for a starting point.
If a number is already in the room, it becomes that starting point.
It does not matter whether the number is relevant.
The brain uses it anyway.
This is one of the most reliable patterns in decision-making research.

@text
A jacket is marked "was 2,400, now 1,200."
The shopper has never paid 2,400 for a jacket.
She does not need a jacket this week.
But the 1,200 feels reasonable next to the 2,400.
If she had seen the same jacket at 1,200 with no "was" sticker, she would have walked past.

@text
A house seller names a price first, deliberately high.
The buyer knows the trick. He has read articles about it.
He offers less than the seller asked.
But his offer still lands closer to the seller's number than he intended.
Knowing the trick did not protect him.

@text
The first number in a decision sets the frame.
Every number that follows is judged relative to it, not on its own.
Designers and marketers use this constantly.
The "premium" option on a pricing page often exists just to make the middle option feel reasonable.
The next package looks at what happens when the brain tries to organize what it sees.

@question
A coffee shop lists a 12-dollar drink at the top of the menu. How does this affect how you perceive a 5-dollar drink below it?

answer: The 5-dollar drink feels like a reasonable choice.
consequence: Exactly. The 12-dollar drink set the reference point. Everything below it feels acceptable by comparison.

answer: It has no effect, people judge prices on their own.
consequence: That would be rational, but the brain does not work that way. The first number shapes the entire frame.

answer: The 5-dollar drink feels expensive.
consequence: The opposite happens. The high anchor makes the lower price feel more acceptable, not less.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The first number in a decision sets the frame. Premium options at the top exist to make mid-range options feel reasonable.
hint: Think about what role the first number plays in your head.

@text
Psychologists call this the <c:g>anchoring effect</c:g>.
The research behind it describes two modes of thought.
System 1 is fast and automatic. System 2 is slow and deliberate.
Anchoring happens because System 1 grabs the first number it sees.
System 2 argues with it, but almost never throws it out.

@true_false
A designer who is aware of the anchoring effect can avoid being influenced by it.

true: True, awareness protects you from anchoring.
consequence: Awareness helps, but less than you would expect. Even statisticians anchor on irrelevant numbers when warned.

false: False, awareness reduces anchoring but does not remove it.
consequence: Right. The bias operates below the level of deliberate thought. The best defense is to set your own number before seeing the anchor.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Knowing about a cognitive bias is not the same as being immune to it. The anchoring effect operates in System 1, which does not respond to knowledge.
hint: Ask whether any unconscious habit has gone away just because you learned about it.

@reflect
A price that felt reasonable only because of the number next to it: a "sale" sticker, a premium option on a pricing page.
A decision where someone else set the first number and your estimate followed it: a salary negotiation, a project deadline.
A moment when you made your own estimate before seeing anyone else's number, and noticed the difference: a used car, a freelance quote.

@package
How the Brain Groups What It Sees

@text
Before the first computer screen was built, a group of psychologists noticed something about how people see.
When shown a collection of dots, people did not see individual dots.
They saw rows, clusters, and shapes.
The brain was organizing the information automatically.
Nobody asked it to.

@text
The simplest of these rules is proximity.
Things that are close together are seen as related.
Things that are far apart are seen as separate.
Your brain does this before you make any conscious decision.
It is automatic, fast, and impossible to turn off.

@text
Every form with neatly grouped fields uses this rule.
Every navigation bar with clustered icons uses it.
Every card layout with consistent spacing uses it.
The spacing alone tells the brain what belongs together.
No label needed.

@text
These organizing rules are called <c:g>Gestalt principles</c:g>.
Proximity is the most basic one, but there are others.
Similarity, closure, and continuity all work the same way.
The brain is always looking for patterns, and always finding them.
Even when the designer did not put them there.

@question
A signup form has "First Name" and "Last Name" fields close together, with "Password" placed far below. What principle is at work?

answer: Proximity, closeness signals that the name fields are related.
consequence: Right. The spacing alone tells the brain these fields belong together, without a label.

answer: Similarity, the fields look the same so they feel grouped.
consequence: Similarity plays a role, but the main cue here is physical distance, not appearance.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Proximity is the most basic Gestalt principle. Adjusting spacing alone communicates relationships without adding any extra visual elements.
hint: Focus on the distance between the elements, not their appearance.

@true_false
Empty space in a design is wasted space that should be filled with content.

true: Every pixel should serve a purpose, empty space is a missed opportunity.
consequence: Empty space is serving a purpose. It gives the brain room to process what is visible.

false: Empty space is a design tool that guides attention and creates structure.
consequence: Right. Without it, everything competes for attention and nothing stands out.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Empty space reduces cognitive load and creates visual structure. The best designs often use more of it, not less.
hint: Think about what makes a simple website feel different from a cluttered one.

@reflect
A screen that felt clean, and whether the clarity came from good content or from generous spacing: a search engine, a weather app.
A design you found cluttered, and whether the problem was too much content or too little space between it: a news site, a settings page.
A form you finished without thinking about it, and whether the grouping of fields made the task feel shorter: an address form, a payment page.
